In .NET 10, MAUI adopted **edge-to-edge** rendering on Android by default, which makes the old `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` ineffective. Here's what to do:

## Recommended Fix

**Option 1 — Use MAUI's built-in keyboard scroll manager (simplest)**

It's enabled by default. Wrap your chat layout so the input is inside a `ScrollView` or at the bottom of a `Grid`, and `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` will push it up. If you previously disabled it, re-enable it:

```csharp
// In your page or a handler
Microsoft.Maui.Platform.KeyboardAutoManagerScroll.Connect(animationDuration: 250);
```

**Option 2 — Respond to keyboard insets manually (more control)**

In your `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:

```csharp
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;

protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

    ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(Window!.DecorView, new InsetsListener());
}

private class InsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
{
    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
    {
        var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
        // imeInsets.Bottom is the keyboard height in pixels
        // Broadcast it to your page via MessagingCenter/WeakReferenceMessenger
        return ViewCompat.OnApplyWindowInsets(v, insets);
    }
}
```

Then in your chat page, add bottom `Padding` equal to the keyboard height.

**Option 3 — Restore legacy resize behavior**

In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:

```csharp
protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);
    Window!.SetSoftInputMode(Android.Views.SoftInput.AdjustResize);
}
```

> ⚠️ This may conflict with edge-to-edge. If it doesn't work alone, also opt out of edge-to-edge by adding to your `<activity>` in `AndroidManifest.xml`:
> ```xml
> android:windowOptOutEdgeToEdgeEnforcement="true"
> ```

---

**TL;DR:** Start with Option 1 — make sure `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` is active and your input bar is in a layout that can shift (bottom of a `Grid` or inside a `ScrollView`). If you need pixel-perfect control for a chat UI, Option 2 with insets gives you the most flexibility.
